\begin_layout Standard
We start with constructing continuous variable kets that satisfy the same
 orthogonality and mutual relations as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle ,\left|1\right\rangle ,\left|+\right\rangle ,\left|-\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle ,\,\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $z\left|0\right\rangle =\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z\left|1\right\rangle =-\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We emphasise that the kets we construct, will not be a countable superposition
 of eigenstates of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 since these are highly idealized and strictly, not even a part of the Hilbert
 space.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We then construct the relavent operators and finally evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle C\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 to show the violation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To construct the states, we start with some definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Unassume: 
\begin_inset Formula $x,\, y,\, z$
\end_inset

 refer to pauli matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula $L\equiv$
\end_inset

some length scale, 
\begin_inset Formula $N\equiv$
\end_inset

number of slits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Consider: A state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\varphi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 s.t.
 (a) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x'|\varphi\right\rangle =\left\langle -x'|\varphi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and (b) it's spread is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ll L$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\varphi_{n}\right\rangle \equiv\int dx'\left\langle x'-nL|\varphi\right\rangle \left|x'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|0'\right\rangle  & \equiv & \frac{1}{\sqrt{N}}\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}\left|\varphi_{2n+1}\right\rangle \\
\left|1'\right\rangle  & \equiv & \frac{1}{\sqrt{N}}\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}\left|\varphi_{2n}\right\rangle 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these states, we construct the analogues of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|+\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|-\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Remark: Definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 justify the word `slit' in the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|+'\right\rangle \equiv\frac{\left|0'\right\rangle +\left|1'\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}},\,\left|-'\right\rangle \equiv\frac{\left|0'\right\rangle -\left|1'\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
NB: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle 0'|1'\right\rangle =0,\,\implies\left\langle +'|-'\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analogous to the spin case, we construct the entangled state 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi'\right\rangle \equiv\frac{\left|+'-'\right\rangle -\left|-'+'\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With these states, we're in a position to construct the relevant Hermitian
 operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\equiv\frac{e^{ipL/\hbar}+e^{-ipL/\hbar}}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
NB: Only in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
X\left|+'\right\rangle  & = & +\left|+'\right\rangle \\
X\left|-'\right\rangle  & = & -\left|-'\right\rangle 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

just as was with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 In general however, the relation doesn't hold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have almost all the cards, except for one that allows for setting {
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

}.
 In the spin case, this was achieved by operating 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\sigma_{z}\phi/2}$
\end_inset

 on the state before measurement.
 Correspondingly, here we define this operator by it's action on the relevant
 state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is defined to be s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U(\phi)\left|0'\right\rangle  & = & e^{i\phi/2}\left|0'\right\rangle \\
U(\phi)\left|1'\right\rangle  & = & e^{-i\phi/2}\left|1'\right\rangle 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can achieved in principle using alternate glass slabs (capacitors)
 for photons (fermions) to adjust the relative phase as desired.
 Alternatively, we could also define 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\phi)$
\end_inset

 in its analytic form as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
